'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Sunday, June 2, 2024 The Jackson County Central boys’ basketball team dominated Marshall Friday night, topping the Tigers 91-57 at home. The JCC girls lost 77-42 to the Tigers on the road. The JCC boys used 13-2 and an 8-0 runs to lead 43-32 at the half and never led by fewer than 11 points in the second half. JCC continued to pull away the second half, outscoring Marshall 48-25 after the break. Roman Voss scored a game-high 26 points and added 11 rebounds, six assists and three steals. Weston Rowe scored 16 of his 18 points in the first half. Ben Gallagher scored 13 points, Grant Freking tallied nine and Thomas Sether had eight. Thomas Liepold, Kasey Grimmius and Noah Thompson each scored five points and Carson Pohlman had two. Aiven Farmer grabbed 11 rebounds and Gallagher had six assists. The win moves the JCC boys to 14-6. They host Redwood Valley Tuesday night. The JCC girls hung with the Tigers early on the road, but trailed 45-32 at the half and then got outscored 32-10 in the second half of a 77-42 loss. Rylie Cother scored 19 points and Brylee Anderson added six for the Huskies, who were without Kylee Wenzel. Zadi Farmer scored four points; Paylin Sether, Aliza Liepold, Emma Haren and Payton Coquyt each scored three; and Madelyn Rowe added one. The loss drops the Huskies to 13-7. They host Caledonia Saturday afternoon. For more on both games, see next week’s paper. The JCC girls lost 77-42 to the Tigers on the road. Stultz With the warmer-than-average temperatures, the Albert Lea Police Department has been able to get a head start for the season on junk vehicle and refuse cleanups throughout the city. JD Carlson Public Safety Director J.D. Carlson said cleanups are typically complaint-driven by a resident or individual who reports it to the police, or by an officer who sees it while out on their normal duties. Carlson said once a complaint comes in, an officer typically will go out and verify the it. A letter typically goes out the next business day advising of city ordinances. Community Service Officer Andy Nelson oversees refuse complaints. Property owners typically have 10 days to comply for grass and refuse complaints and two weeks for junk vehicles. Carlson said most of the time when someone sees a letter from the city, the issue takes care of itself, but in the event that it does not, they then work to line up services to abate the problem. He said they have two service providers they use for refuse, depending on the size of the concern, and then they bill the cost back to the property owner. The service is not done by city employees. “It comes down to our police mission statement of enhancing the quality of life in Albert Lea,” Carlson said. “Our services attempt to do that.” He said the quality of life is important for both current residents and those looking to move to the community.'}]

Enterprise Dispatch, Delano Herald Journal, McLeod County Chronicle, Arlington Enterprise, & West Carver News Wallace “Wally” Henry Tanke, age 69, of Lester Prairie, died Sunday, Nov. 4, 2007 at the Glencoe Regional Health Services. He was born Feb. 25, 1938 in Litchfield, the son of Walter and Erna Buckentine Tanke. Wally was baptized March 13, 1938 at Emanuel Lutheran Church in Hamburg, and instructed in the Lutheran Catechism and confirmed in the Christian faith April 6, 1952 at the same church. Wally was formerly employed at The Dodge House in Lester Prairie as a bartender for 17 years. He also had worked for Radtke Excavating and Central By Products. He is survived by his loving companion and best friend, Lois Fiecke; sons Greg Tanke of Arizona, Jeff Tanke of Wood Lake, James Tanke of Hamburg, Jeremy Fiecke and fiancée Alyssa Braun of Watertown, and Ryan Fiecke of New Germany; a stepson, Chris Fiecke of Lester Prairie; eight grandchildren; and one great-grandchild. Wally is further survived by his mother, Erna Tanke of Hamburg; extended family Leona Fiecke of Lester Prairie, Carol Pogue and special friend Terry Thomson of Chisago City, Joan (Alan) Teubert of Hutchinson, Janet Grimm and special friend Loren Karnes of LeSueur, Marilyn (Doug) Ranzau of Glencoe, and Renee (Kent) Glessing of Hutchinson; and other relatives and friends. He was preceded in death by a son, Rodney Dittmer; his father, Walter Tanke; and his father-in-law, Eugene Fiecke. Funeral services were Thursday, Nov. 8 at 1 p.m. at the Prairie Evangelical U.C.C. in Lester Prairie with the Rev. William Baldwin officiating. Interment followed at Church of God Cemetery in Bergen Township. Friends called Wednesday, Nov. 7 from 4 to 8 p.m. at the Chilson Funeral Home in Winsted. Casket bearers were Craig Mitchell, Pat Nebben, Greg Gatz, Gene Feltmann, Glen Templin, and Bob Kruschke. The Chilson Funeral Home in Winsted served the family. human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Tensions grew between the Hamline student body and Hamline’s contracted dining service provider Aramark this past fall, as Hamline students’ personal and moral frustrations with the company came to light. Now with the request for proposal (RFP) process underway, students may see changes by next fall. After Hamline University’s Student Congress (HUSC) unanimously passed a resolution on Sept. 19, calling on the university to find a new dining service provider, Dean of Students Patti Klein-Kersten started the initial steps of an RFP process, a process which alerts food service vendors that Hamline is accepting contract proposals. With the RFP process officially in progress, a team has been assembled to consider both the students and the university’s needs in selecting a new contract. The selection committee is made up of students Hafsa Ahmed and Oliver Engstrom, faculty member Patti Born Selly and staff members Kelly Rudney, Jen Olsen Krengel, Ken Dehkes. The committee is co-chaired by Klein-Kersten and Athletic Director Alex Focke. In September, students were given space to share their personal experiences with dining at Hamline. In a series of Food Advisory Committee meetings led by Yolanda Hansen and Nick Ortega, Director of Residential Life and Director of Dining Services, respectively, students came prepared with many shared and some unique frustrations they encountered in their experiences dining at Hamline. The meetings gave direction to Nick Ortega for specific changes to be implemented to make dining more accessible and inclusive, leading to the reopening of the Piper Grill this semester. “Our goal was always to reopen Piper Grill,” Ortega wrote in an email. “It has been one of my top goals since the day I moved into the director’s role. I’m happy that we are able to have it open to help enhance the late night options we have on campus.” For some students, the increase in accessibility and inclusivity is positive, but the timing of reopening in relation to the upcoming RFP committee decisions makes the motivations questionable. “It’s certainly a good thing that it’s open for food access on campus, it’s better to have it than not have it, but it absolutely is something where they’re choosing now as an opportune time, given the pressure and, you know, threats against the contract that they currently have,” Matthew Maroney said. Maroney is a member of Feed Your Brain (FYB) a student organization that advocates for food equity on campus. During fall semester, FYB became active objectors to Aramark, including holding a protest in November outside of Anderson Center where dining services is housed, specifically citing Aramark’s In2Work program as the basis of the protest. AJ Escalante, also of FYB, shared similar thoughts about the timing of the Piper Grill’s reopening. “It seems almost performative, especially given the context of [Hamline’s] already in the middle of getting proposals for food service providers,” Escalante said. Though both Escalante and Maroney applied to be a part of the selection committee, neither was selected to be student representatives. “We do want to make sure that … people with non-student considerations being a part of this process don’t forget who they’re doing it for, and that they do remember that they’re doing this to serve a community and not just for the financials,” Escalante said. The committee will meet on April 25 and 26 to hear presentations from potential contractors and ask questions before sending a recommendation to President Murray. 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': "Sponsored By ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT BLOOMINGTON, Minn. — The U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service is tightening requirements imposed on the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources when the state wants to cut trees in wildlife management areas. The federal agency is essentially asking the state to prove that any logging on WMAs has wildlife management as its primary purpose at each logging site and not simply cutting trees for the state’s timber industry. The feds say they will withhold money for each proposed project until the state proves the wildlife purpose. The new requirements are just the latest twist in an ongoing saga over how much, where and why timber should be cut on the state’s 1,440 public wildlife management areas, at least those that have trees. The state has another 700 aquatic management areas covering some 700 miles of shoreline on lakes and rivers, much of it forested. The debate impacts a relatively small amount of the state’s share of timber. Most of the state's DNR-managed timber comes from state forests and is not subject to the issues over wildlife management areas. ADVERTISEMENT The latest twist comes after the federal agency last year withheld some $21 million in federal sporting goods tax revenues from Minnesota because DNR officials hadn't satisfied federal requirements on managing the wildlife management areas. It’s those federal funds that are used to acquire and manage wildlife and aquatic management areas and that money is earmarked for wildlife and fish purposes only. Critics of the DNR’s logging policies in wildlife management areas say the agency had been ignoring its own wildlife managers over where, when and how logging should occur on the public lands. The added requirements imposed by the Fish & Wildlife Service should help keep the DNR on its pledged course of putting wildlife first in all logging projects on the public hunting areas. “There have never been site-specific requirements like this before in Minnesota,’’ said Craig Sterle, a former DNR forester who has been critical of the agency on the issue. “The two sides really aren’t that far apart when it comes down to how many acres (to be logged) are involved. No one has argued that timber harvest shouldn’t be part of wildlife management on these lands. It’s just a matter of how and why you do it. ... It’s the why that’s the issue here,’’ said Gary Drotts, a former DNR biologist. The latest details, included in a letter from the federal agency to the DNR, were made public by the group Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility. A federal agency official confirmed the letter but hasn't yet commented on the issue. Dave Olfelt, DNR Fish and Wildlife Division director, said the goal of the new conditions is documenting, in writing, the wildlife purposes of a particular logging project in a transparent way. This documentation does not increase or decrease the number of acres DNR will log, he noted. “DNR requested more precise language in the conditions, and the USFWS concurred that this would be helpful,’’ Olfelt said. “It’s important to understand that the conditions are not substantively different from those in our 2021 grant. Rather, they are more specific as to the documentation that is required, when in the process we provide that documentation and the process for the USFWS to review DNR’s documentation.” The issue has been festering for nearly five years as conservationists, including several current and retired DNR wildlife biologists, argue the DNR is planning to log too much and in the wrong places on some wildlife areas to benefit the timber industry, often to the detriment of wildlife habitat. ADVERTISEMENT Pressured by those critics, the Fish and Wildlife Service stepped in and issued orders to the state, including a lengthy letter of agreement signed by both sides last March scolding the DNR for dragging its feet on the issue. The dispute, first reported in the News Tribune in August 2019, began when top DNR officials began implementing a timber availability report that called for more trees to be cut on state lands to feed the state's timber industry, including more timber from wildlife management areas. The effort began under then-Gov. Mark Dayton, and top DNR officials have continued to press for more logging under Gov. Tim Walz. The effort called for increasing the state's share of wood for the industry from 800,000 cords annually to 870,000 cords, and asked for part of the increase to come from wildlife management areas. In a 2019 letter to Strommen, 28 DNR wildlife managers described any industry-aimed increase in logging on wildlife areas as scientifically dishonest. They said concerns raised by wildlife staff were being ignored by DNR forestry staff and top DNR officials. But Strommen has said that, while wildlife area logging will be included as part of the total state timber sold to the timber industry, the agency has no quotas on how much timber must come from wildlife management areas. She has called critics' complaints unwarranted and misguided, saying they have misunderstood the timber availability analysis from the start. This story was updated at 10:16 a.m. Jan. 11 with comments from the DNR. It was originally posted at 10 a.m. Jan. 11. ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT"}]

Updated: June 2, 2024 @ 12:38 am It can all be gone in an instant. A single dad of five is trying to pick up the pieces after he and his family lost everything in a fire. “I pulled up right before the fire department arrived. I had a sinking pit in my stomach as soon as I turned down the street because the proximity looked like it was either my house or my neighbor’s house. I knew something was not good,” Lino Lakes resident Maisen Saxton recalled. “The bottom line is I’m thankful that everybody was safe. Not everybody is that fortunate … We are just trying to do best we can to pick up the pieces and keep in good spirits.” When the fire broke out, no one was home. Saxton ran to Walmart to pick up a few last-minute things they needed to host Christmas Eve dinner. His parents, who live across the street, were also helping prepare for the meal. While Maisen was gone, family members were running between the two houses. “They were using the oven to heat up some dishes for dinner … They left thinking there wouldn’t be any issue,” Saxton recalled. “Thirty minutes later, they got a knock on the door from my neighbor saying your house is on fire.” Saxton’s father went over to try to put the fire out, but at that point Saxton said it was too late. “It was an accident, it was tragic, it’s been devastating, but blaming anybody and should’ve, could’ve, would haves aren’t going to do anything,” he said. “If my windshield wiper didn’t break, and I didn’t go back (into WalMart), I may have been home. I’m pretty sure I would have at least seen it and I probably could have put it out. There is nothing I can do about it now. It could have gone differently with a number of different variables, but it didn’t, and we are where we are.” Saxton, originally from Oregon, has lived in Lino Lakes for 2 1/2 years. He purchased the home from his parents. He is now staying right across the street from their damaged home in his parents’ home with his two children, ages 8 and 10, and three foster children, ages 10, 12 and 14. Saxton is a Metro Transit driver. As a single dad of two, he said being a foster parent was not something that was ever on his radar. “I felt like things were plenty difficult enough. I didn’t need any more on my plate,” he said. Long story short, a neighbor a few doors down from them fell on some hard times. The three kids started spending more and more time at Saxton’s house. Child Protective Services eventually got involved, and now Saxton is considered a “kinship foster.” For the foreseeable future, the children will remain with him. The hope is that that their mother will be able to care for them again one day. “It’s been a wild and unexpected ride,” Saxton said. Unexpected support Since Saxton has only been in Minnesota for a couple of years, he was not expecting the outpouring of support he and his family have received since the Christmas Eve tragedy. “In this unforeseen tragedy, we have been really blessed with unexpected support from the local community,” Saxton said. “That has been really cool to see. It’s been a huge help and encouragement to keep my head up.” Robyn and Lindsay Smith know Saxton and his family through sports, as Saxton coached their son’s baseball team. “We know the family and were heartbroken to hear that they lost everything,” Robyn said. “I immediately reached out to Maisen to see what they needed and how we could help … He gave me a list, and I got to work.” The two set out to see what donations they could round up, and ended up finding support through a church congregation and social media. Saxton says he sent a list of items the family could use and next thing he knew, a U-Haul showed up with everything on the list and then some. “I was blown away; other than coaching their son in baseball, I’ve had very minimal contact with them,” he said. “It leaves me dumbfounded and speechless.” Robyn added, “Maisen’s a great dad and a really nice person. He would do anything for his kids. We just wanted to be able to help him however we could. I really hope the community will rally around him and help him in this time of need.” Many people have stepped up to help the family by providing clothes, furniture and even cash donations. As of press deadline, a GoFundMe had raised over $15,000. “The support just made it so much more bearable. I don’t feel the hopelessness and I can fight the urge to break down in tears when I step into the place because I know how much support we have,” he said. “We are going to be okay.” To donate, visit: https://gf.me/v/c/lmgs/fire-of-christmas-eve Managing Editor Shannon Granholm can be reached at 651-407-1227 or quadnews@presspubs.com Log In Keep it Clean. This Minnesota winter could be the the mildest on record, but it will still be a relief when the landscape finally comes back to life. Updated: June 2, 2024 @ 12:06 am Now, more than ever, the world needs trustworthy reporting—but good journalism isn’t free. Please support us by subscribing or making a contribution. Elim Lutheran Church Pastor Seth Perry is no stranger to the challenges that mental health conditions can cause. Worse yet, the prevailing stigma makes it difficult to talk about one’s mental health and receive the help they need. To combat the stigma and make mental health a priority in his community, Perry started a campaign to raise awareness about mental health in February of 2023. Continuing in that pursuit, Elim is hosting a Lenten Mental Health Dinner Feb. 21 to kick off the Our Stigma campaign this year. Perry, originally from Vancouver, British Columbia became a pastor in 2017 and remained a pastor in Canada until 2019 when he moved to Scandia. By August of 2022, he was the pastor at Elim Lutheran Church. Having personal experience with the impact of his own mental health conditions, he made the effort to raise awareness last year at Elim. “Last year, I thought there was a need in a lot of our congregations to have a broader discussion and deeper education about mental health conditions,” said Perry. “People come to church and a lot of them are in a state of need and a lot of that is tied to their own mental health. But I saw that many people didn't feel comfortable talking about their own mental health. “I knew that I was one of those people. I knew the people that were coming to the church either had family members with mental health conditions or they themselves had a mental health condition and they needed to hear some support.” Perry had been diagnosed with Bipolar type 1 in his mid-twenties but had struggled with the condition since he was a teenager. In order to break the stigma of talking about mental health, Perry decided to inform his congregation of his diagnosis last year. “I thought it was time for me to share that openly with the congregation and see how they would respond,” Perry said. “And the response was great. I think it was twofold. A lot of people who have family members that are affected by mental health conditions came to me and needed help and understand their loved ones, but also individuals who were in crisis started to come to the church more and feel comfortable coming to this place and to ask for help. “I didn't expect it to be that successful, but that's what our last year of ministry at Elim Lutheran Church has been focused around was finding help for individuals who are in crisis and allowing family members to be more comfortable asking for help about their loved ones and to realize that they're not alone.” With the overwhelming success of the first campaign last year, Perry has worked with local organizations to continue the progress made toward helping those with mental health struggles. From Feb. 21 through March 20, the Our Stigma campaign will help raise awareness for all those affected by various mental health conditions and the stigma of speaking out about them. “I've been overwhelmed with the amount of people that need help and want to talk about getting help. That really points to a larger societal crisis we're in the midst of right now. I think there's not enough accessibility to care for individuals who are in crisis or who need to see professionals, and that's happening right here in Washington and Chisago counties. “The goal of the campaign is to connect the various community organizations so we can serve the community better… I think that we're providing a forum where we can further the dialogue. And a church is a great intermediary space. We have the physical space, we have a volunteers and we can start helping people make connections in order to better the health of community members here.” The Our Stigma campaign kickoff starts Feb. 21 at the Elim Lutheran Church Lenten Mental Health Dinner. This is a “pay what you can” dinner and no one is turned away. Tickets are for sale in advance at the Elim Lutheran Church Office. Proceeds go to the Scandia Marine Food Shelf. Dinner is served at 5:15 p.m. and a candlelight vigil will be held in the sanctuary at 7 p.m. Then a PTSD Awareness Potluck event will be held March 20 at the Elim Lutheran Church. The dinner starts a 5:15 p.m. and all are invited to bring a dish to share. Founder of the Invisible Wounds Project Russ Hanes will be featured at this event and a free will offering will be available for The Invisible Wounds Project of Forest Lake. Throughout the campaign the National Alliance on Mental Illnesses (NAMI) is teaching an hour and a half long suicide prevention class. Those dates are February 28th at 10:30 AM March 16th at 10:30 AM and March 23rd at 10:30 AM There are 30 spots available in each class 90 total. Please give us a call at 218-736-7511 Copyright © • Wick Communications Terms of Use | Privacy Policy Mike Frisch with a walleye caught from a weed edge. As a fishing TV host/fishing educator one of my goals is to help people catch more fish. Here is a look at three things that anglers can do this coming season that can help them increase their fishing skills and hopefully catch more fish! Embrace change With the vast increase in water clarity that many of our lakes have seen in the last dozen years or so, successful anglers have recognized this change and, most importantly, adapted to the situation. For example, when chasing walleyes, I find myself fishing more and more in and around weeds, or targeting much deeper waters. It’s my thought that many of today’s walleyes seek the shade and cover that weeds offer. Or they avoid the increased light penetration that clear water creates by heading much deeper. Simply put, back in the day we fished the edges of classic walleye structure like underwater points and sunken humps, often with water that was in the 15–25-foot range. Today, however those fish might be up shallower in the weeds on the tops of that structure or slid out deeper into the basin adjacent to the humps and points. Embracing change regarding fish location is important, but so is learning fishing techniques better suited for where the fish now hold. For example, in the past, walleye anglers relied on Lindy-style rigs and jig/minnow combinations for fishing the structure mentioned above. Those methods will still catch some fish, but weed walleyes are often targeted by the modern walleye angler pitching jigs tipped with plastics or throwing slip bobbers to pockets in the weeds. And a heavy 3- or even 4-ounce bottom bouncer tipped with a plain snell and a nightcrawler is a great way to pursue those fish that have slid out a bit and now are in maybe 40 to 50 feet of water. Be a line watcher I grew up a walleye angler, eventually became a basshead and now consider myself a multi-species angler. One thing bass fishing taught me that helps catch fish of all species is the importance of watching my fishing line, particularly when casting lures. Often, for example, when I pitch a jig/plastic to bass, my line twitches on the bite. Walleye jig pitchers can also see bites. Several falls back, guide clients and I were on a good bite pitching 1/8-ounce jigs and minnows to shallow weeds. Smaller walleyes were just “felt” as the line and rod tip got heavy. Once in a while, however, the fishing line would slowly start to swim off to the side. Those were usually bigger walleyes in the 4- to 8-pound range! If you weren’t paying attention, those fish would drop the jig minus a hookset. To facilitate seeing more bites, I often use hi-vis braided line in combination with a short fluorocarbon leader. The hi vis braid is very sensitive and visible, while the fluoro leader is invisible to the fish. CONTRA Braid in the yellow color is spooled on lots of my rods, allowing my fishing partners and me to see and feel more bites and set more hooks. Fish more Learning about fish behavior, various technologies and fishing techniques is important to upping your fishing game. However, nothing beats time on the water! It’s no coincidence that the best anglers I know are also those who spend the most time on the water. The age-old saying “practice makes perfect” holds true to fishing. While perfection probably won’t happen in the fishing world, anglers can often up their game by spending more time on the water, and by putting to use some of the tips presented above regarding embracing change and line watching too. As always, good luck on the water and remember to include a youngster in your next outdoors adventure! Mike Frisch is the host of the popular Fishing the Midwest TV series. Visit www.fishingthemidwest.com or follow Fishing the Midwest on Facebook for more "fishy" stuff. Have a question? spouses at the Minnesota Veterans Homes-Fergus Falls. The Disabled American Veterans (DAV) Chapter 25 donated $10,000 to support the new construction of a Memorial Wall adjacent to the existing wall. The current Memorial Wall, also known as The Walk of Honor was constructed in 2004 after the March 1998 opening of the Home. The Wall lists each of the 854 Residents who have passed away while living in the Home. The existing Wall has just enough space for one last engraving in early-May for those Residents who have passed during the previous 12 months. The Walk of Honor is one way the Veterans Home honors and remembers each person listed so family and friends can gather to pay their respects and reflect on the sacrifices made by those who served our country. The Fergus Falls DAV uses the funds collected from clothes deposited in the large lime-green bins scattered around the community “to give back to fellow Veterans in need and other community projects.” “The Veterans Home is proud to accept this gift on behalf of our 78 Residents and future Residents, who gave unselfishly and made sacrifices to protect our great nation. This new wall will represent the names of approximately 1,000 Residents over the next 25 years. We are thankful for the thoughtful generosity of those military members who do great work for our Disabled American Veterans,” said Gary Harris Jr., public affairs official at the Fergus Falls Veterans Home, in a news release. ADVERTISEMENT The Minnesota Veterans Homes-Fergus Falls is a state-run, skilled nursing facility whose mission is to serve Veterans and their families. For the past two years, the Home has been recognized as one of the Best Long-term Care Nursing Homes by U.S. News & World Report. ADVERTISEMENT'}]

human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'A longitudinal study published Jan 30 in Frontiers in Public Health shows Black, Indigenous, people of color (BIPOC) Covid-19 patients in America had greater post-Covid-19 burdens than non-Hispanic, White peers. The long-term negative consequences were seen in health status, activity level and missed work, despite White and BIPOC patients having similar initial symptoms of infections. The findings are part of the ongoing INSPIRE study, a collaboration of eight major academic medical centers looking at the long-term effects of Covid-19. Hispanics reported more poor heath “While we don’t know what caused these different impacts, we know that these populations can have a harder time accessing health care, which may complicate their recovery,” said study author Kari Stephens, Ph.D., of the University of Washington School of Medicine in a University of Washington press release on the study. The study was based on self-reported differences in symptoms and health-related impacts three and six months after the first SARS-CoV-2 infection documented from December 2020 to July 2022. Included were 2,402 adults with Covid-19 and 759 negative controls. Fourteen percent of Covid-19-positive participants were Hispanic, 11.0 percent were Asian, 7.9 percent were Black, 9.9 percent were other/multiple races, and 71.1 percent were White. Surveys included a list of 22 symptoms, including fatigue and shortness of breath. At three months, Hispanic participants were more likely than non-Hispanic participants to report fair or poor health. But by six months, differences by ethnicity were not present among Hispanics. At three months, Asian participants were more likely to report fair/poor health at the same rate as White participants, but at six months Asians were more likely to report poor health. Black participants report missing more work At three months, reports of more than five missed workdays were similar across all race groups. But by six months, reports of missed work were much higher among Black participants. Compared to White respondents, Black respondents who had Covid six months prior were almost three times as likely to report missed work. The authors said this difference may be due to the types of jobs Black Americans have compared to White Americans, including more often being essential workers. “Higher loss of work days may be driven by the overrepresentation of minority populations in physically demanding frontline industries without the option to work from home,” the authors wrote. “Increased focus on understanding drivers of ethnic and racial differences in health impacts may inform approaches to advance health equity after SARS-CoV-2 infection.” Stephanie Soucheray is a news reporter for CIDRAP News. www.cidrap.umn.edu. '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'At least 21 people are injured after an explosion Monday rippled through the bottom floors of a hotel building in downtown Fort Worth, Texas, authorities said. One person was in critical condition and four others were seriously injured, MedStar spokesperson Matt Zavadsky said at a news briefing Monday. The rest had minor injuries. Craig Trojacek, a spokesperson for the Fort Worth Fire Department, said the first call of a fire at Sandman Signature Fort Worth Downtown Hotel was received at around 3:32 p.m. local time. Multiple calls about an explosion came in after. The smell of gas permeated through downtown Fort Worth, Trojacek later said, adding that investigators are confident the blast was "some kind of gas explosion." Photos of the explosion showed windows and debris blown out and scattered across the street. The fire department said Monday evening the blast no longer posed any public safety issues to downtown Fort Worth, but crews would be on the scene all night to continue search efforts and ensure no one was trapped. Desiree Partain of MedStar, which provides ambulance and emergency medical services in Fort Worth, said medics treated four people on the scene but did not take them to a hospital. According to Trojacek, investigators are working with federal investigators to determine the cause of the blast. The scene, Trojacek added, had left rescue teams unable to immediately reach some parts of the building. "We had reports of people trapped down in the basement, and because of the explosion that took place, some of those access areas were either covered up or it didn’t feel safe at that point to get people down into," Trojacek said. Developing into the night: For an update, sign up for USA TODAY\'s Evening Briefing newsletter Mike Vanca was staying at the hotel but was not inside when the explosion happened. He was in a nearby office and still felt the shockwave from the explosion. "The building shook like someone slapped the side of it with your hand," Vanca told KDFW. "So it was very loud and very violent." Hunter Chacon, an employee at nearby Wicked Butcher, told the Dallas Morning News that he arrived to downtown shortly after the blast as first responders were still pouring in. He ran toward the commotion before he was stopped about three blocks from the hotel. “From there, I could definitely smell the gas,” Chacon said. The 245-room Sandman Signature Fort Worth Downtown Hotel dates to 1920, according to the hotel’s website, and is located in a busy area of downtown about one block from the Fort Worth Convention Center. The building, known as “The Waggoner Building,” has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places since 1979. Sandman Hotel in Fort Worth said Monday that due to damage from the blast, it won\'t be taking bookings “until further notice.” The hotel did not immediately return USA TODAY’s request for comment. Trojacek said a restaurant in the building had been under construction but said it was not definitive that is where the blast occurred. Kristin Goodspeed, a spokesperson for natural gas provider Atmos Energy, told USA TODAY that technicians were on the scene at the request of the city’s fire department. "Gas has been isolated to the affected area, and we will continue to assist the Fort Worth Fire and Police Departments and all officials in support of their investigation," Goodspeed said. Texas Gov. Greg Abbott said he had been in contact with local officials following the blast and was ready to "immediately deploy any additional personnel and resources needed to keep Texans in the area safe and out of harm’s way." Contributing: The Associated Press'}]

written entirely by a human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT BAXTER — Twenty-five potential parcels of public land were whittled down to eight and then two as the top choices to create a Baxter dog park. The No. 1 choice is city-owned land near the intersection of Clearwater and Inglewood Drive for its low cost, accessibility, soil and topography, screening and proximity to high density housing. The property covers 27.2 acres, much of it wooded with a wetland on one side. In addition to the park itself, the property has the potential to provide walking trails for leashed dogs, an area for parking and an option to have a dedicated site for smaller dogs. “So we really thought this had a lot of opportunity for the future, very close to a lot of high density, to residential that people can walk from,” said Consultant Jillian Reiner, Widseth landscape architect who presented the options. “It’s connected to trails on the same side of the street.” Reiner said there is a large benefit to having a dog park in a wooded area because of the shade, which is an important factor. She said shade is the number one ask for a dog park. The second choice property is the city’s North Water Tower property at the intersection of Woida Road and Inglewood Drive. The area is largely open with screening on the perimeter of the 3.2 acres. It is also close to high density housing, is low cost, accessible and meets the other metrics for distance from a residence. Reiner noted there aren’t many ways the site can be used. One thing that could increase the cost may be the need to move the entrance farther away from the busier street intersection. ADVERTISEMENT “We wanted to be close to some trails and we wanted people to be able to walk,” Reiner said, noting national studies they reviewed noted people who use dog parks really like to be able to walk their dog there. The distance goal was a quarter-mile to a half-mile from their apartment. The idea of being closer to higher density housing was to give dog owners who don’t have much greenspace, a place to go and utilize the benefits of a dog park. Reiner said it’s possible some of the city owned parcels that weren’t on the top of the list this time could work at a later date for another dog park as the city grows. Other city-owned locations on the short list included an 11.4 acre site on Oakwood Drive, a 2.4 acres property on Hastings Road, a 1.2 acre site by Clearwater Road and Forest Drive, a 4.6 acre site by Southdale Park and a 17.7 acre site called Whipple Woods by Whipple Beach, and a 1.5 acre site by Hinckley Road. Council member Jeff Phillips wondered if there would be a requirement for people who used the park to license their dogs through the city. Reiner said that isn’t typical and would be challenging to manage. She noted people who travel also look for dog parks. Council member Zach Tabatt said he’d like a full analysis of whether the currently vacant land just to the south of Clearwater Road would be developed, perhaps with another apartment building going up there. In that case, since the parcel is large, Tabatt wondered if there was a different access point for a parking lot to that site for a dog park there. Council member Connie Lyscio has been a longstanding advocate of adding a dog park in the city. Priorities in scoring for potential parcels The study noted future sites that may work for a potential future dog park as the city grows. It determined a single 1.5 acre dog park would accommodate the estimated 9,400 residents of Baxter (based on the 2021 Census) that is growing at 2.2% annually along with 85,250 people in the greater Brainerd Micropolitan Area (which includes Crow Wing and Cass counties) and about 76,000 people visiting or driving through Baxter regularly, especially during the summer. ADVERTISEMENT Design guidelines Baxter dog licenses issued There isn’t a dedicated open house to get feedback on a dog park but the top two options for the park will be included in the open house for Oscar Kristofferson Park development options . That open house is from 6-8 p.m. Feb. 29 at City Hall. The city’s goal is to construct the dog park this year. Renee Richardson, managing editor, may be reached at 218-855-5852 or renee.richardson@brainerddispatch.com. Follow on Twitter at @DispatchBizBuzz. ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT'}]

'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': "In today’s world people seem to be separated and isolated from community. With the use of technology, we can be plugged in to a device watching our own video or reading our own news or learning about our own interests. We communicate with others via text, or any number of social media platforms. It is common when in a public space to have many people in proximity but nobody communicating directly with each other. People are on their phones, with earbuds in. It is interesting that we have a self-imposed isolation. There are exceptions, once people have established a connection with a group that they feel comfortable with, there tends to be more willingness to invest. I’m thinking of a club, or a coffee group, or occasionally even work friends. These groups can fulfill a social need that we have. Activation will allow you to view unlimited online articles each month. To activate your Premium online account, the email address and phone number provided with your paid newspaper subscription needs to match the information you use in setting up your online user account. If you are having trouble or want to confirm what email address and phone number is listed on your subscription account, please call 952-345-6682 or email circulation@swpub.com and we'll be happy to assist. To say that Cooper’s Foods is an institution in the Chaska community is an understatement. Opened more than 100 years ago in 1917 by current owner Gary Cooper’s grandparents, Joe and Rose, the store has weathered good times and bad expanding to a chain of, at its peak, seven stores across the Midwest. Cooper’s Chaska location is set to close in less than a month, leaving the St. Paul store as the only remaining family operation. Large national chains have moved into the community over the past decade, making it progressively more difficult to compete. Since the start of the Highway 41 construction project, according to Cooper, sales dropped 10%. “Frankly, I think Chaska is losing something,” says Cooper of the pending store closure. Cooper’s started not as a grocery store, but as a “cash store” buying and selling goods, including groceries. As reported in this newspaper in 1917: “J. Cooper and family moved into the Mrs. Schmidt residence in the first ward last week. Mr. Cooper is a junk dealer and expects to engage entirely in that business.” Joe Cooper turned the store over to his son and daughter-in-law, Jake and Lillian, in 1942. Again from the Chaska Herald of that year, “Jake and Lillian Cooper, new owners of the popular Cooper’s store in Chaska have, in a scant six weeks, transformed the old stand, so ablely managed through the years by Mr. and Mrs. Joe Cooper, into a supermarket in all that the word implies.” It was under his parent’s ownership, Gary Cooper began working at the store at age 11. The store was expanded several times in the following decades, with other stores opened by the Coopers in Jonathan and Plymouth. In 1977, still under Jake and Lillian’s ownership, the store relocated from downtown Chaska, to Walnut Street where it remains to this day. Over the years, competition from big box stores like Target, Rainbow Foods, Aldi, and Cub has increased. In 1996 Rainbow Foods moved in at the intersection of Highway 41 and Pioneer Trail, beating out a potential expansion for Cooper’s. With Costco set to open a within a few miles from the Chaska store later this year, another competitor “is not a threat, it’s a reality,” says Cooper. Cooper has previously called big box stores “predatory” in how they can cut prices that are difficult to match by smaller stores, and in the end, may eventually be driven out of business. Some larger national chains sell milk for cheaper than his cost, says Cooper, citing a Minnesota law that puts a floor on the price of milk in the state for all but during the month of June. “I don’t know how they can do that,” says Cooper. Cooper met with city officials on Jan. 29 in order to work out a deal to keep the doors of his grocery store open. The option discussed would have designated the land around Cooper’s Chaska location to be sold to a land trust and leased back to Cooper’s for a minimum price. This arrangement has been used by the city previously, but only to create affordable housing. “We haven’t ever proposed that for a commercial property, but we thought it was important,” said City Administrator Matt Podhradsky. While the proposal would have theoretically lowered operating costs for Cooper’s, funds would be needed to set up the land trust and renovations to the store would be required in order to meet state laws. Cooper said the plan was “reasonable and made sense, but based on the sales trends I’ve seen and the money I’ve been losing, I decided to not continue.” While this decision marks the end of not just an era, but of several, Cooper is glad to have come to a decision. “I have less anxiety today than when I was deciding,” he concluded. With less than a month left in business, Cooper’s new focus is on selling their remaining product stock. Discounts of 25% can already be found on store shelves. Price cuts will increase as the store moves towards its final days, he said. “One way the community can help and one of the things we need is to turn that inventory into cash,” says Cooper. Part of his focus is on “making employees whole,” says Cooper, citing the funds will be needed to pay out employees for earned sick days and PTO. Though the store’s time in Chaska is coming to an end, Cooper is grateful for the ride. “Even though I don’t like the ending, it was a good story,” says Cooper. Cooper’s Food will be open until March 2 and is located at 710 Walnut St. Sorry, there are no recent results for popular articles. The Women’s Foundation of Minnesota announced $375,000 in general operating renewal grants to 19 organizations. In addition to the organizations receiving a second year of funding through the Fund for Safety , Women’s Foundation of Minnesota awarded a $50,000 grant to Minnesota Coalition Against Sexual Assault to be a backbone support organization for the field. Sexual Assault Services Inc. in Brainerd received $15,000 to resource a Sexual Assault Nurse Examiner program in Brainerd, where the closest program is more than an hour away. Funding will support the hiring of a program coordinator, which will train medical professionals in the program curriculum, including use of sexual assault kits, trauma-response training, and evidence collection. In total, the awards represent an investment of $425,000 through its Fund for Safety. Funding a backbone organization to maintain strategic coherence in the field comes in response to listening sessions with grantee-partners , who also share a vision of a culture of healing, healthy relationships, inclusion, and community care. More people. Minnesota’s employment and population trends are going in the right direction, which should create cautious optimism going into 2024. The data, derived from recent reports from the Department of Employment and Economic Development ( DEED ) as well as the U.S. Census Bureau, show stable, steady growth in both areas. In a credit to the state’s employers and workers, Minnesota has added jobs for five months straight and 9,500 more from October to November. That’s the largest increase since January. And the state gained 17,300 jobs over a three-month period, a 0.6% increase, compared with a 0.2% increase in the same time frame nationally. November’s state unemployment rate fell to 3.1%, impressively below the 3.7% national rate, as eight of 10 “supersectors” (as DEED deems them) saw growth, including trade, transportation and utilities (up 3,300 jobs); education and health services (up 2,700); government (up 1,100), and manufacturing (up 1,000). But reflecting an enduring challenge to Minnesota employers and the state itself, the labor force actually decreased by 7,433 people in November, dropping Minnesota’s participation rate to 68.3%. That’s still well above the 62.8% national average, but below what’s needed for most employers facing chronic labor shortages — a particularly acute condition in southern Minnesota, Angelina Nguyen, DEED labor market information director, said during a virtual news conference last Thursday. DEED will continue to roll out workforce development initiatives in 2024, Commissioner Matt Varilek said during the news conference, in which he also commented on the positive population growth of 23,615 people from July 2022 to July 2023. While the 0.4% increase isn’t as high as some rapidly growing Sun Belt states — as well as neighboring North and South Dakota — it’s better than the previous two years, and more in line with Minnesota’s typical trend line. Some of the increase came from post-pandemic stabilization of natural growth (births minus deaths), which accounted for 13,834 more Minnesotans, and even more from international migration, which added 14,575 new Minnesotans. But domestic out-migration — Minnesotans moving to other states — continued, albeit at a slower pace of 4,686. The overall population growth “is a positive thing for all those employers that have more demand for workers than they can find,” Varilek said. “Beyond that, I would say we hope to continue supporting that trend and inviting Minnesotans by being a welcoming place.” It already is for jobseekers — and government, institutions and individuals can make it even more welcoming. But it’s crucial that state leaders focus on retaining residents and attracting people from other states. International migration is highly dependent on domestic politics, and an incoming Republican presidential administration (especially under former President Donald Trump) may have much more restrictive immigration policies than the Biden administration has had. State government, under DFL leadership at the executive and legislative level, took several steps last session to try to differentiate Minnesota from neighboring states, including with programs like paid family leave. Next session, legislative leaders, as well as Gov. Tim Walz, should proceed with caution, however, because of impending budget restraints as well the need to adjust to the significant investments made last session, many of which will also require new workers to implement. “I think we should all take pride in the unique strengths of the Minnesota economy,” Varilek said, commenting on its structural diversity, high prosperity, high incomes and relatively low unemployment. Within the Upper Midwest, Minnesota “has really taken a distinct, strategic approach to policy,” he added as he reflected on initiatives in education and other sectors. “We think those things are going to give us an advantage as people learn more about the Minnesota story, and learn more about the Minnesota quality of life.” It’s a story that should indeed be heard regionally, nationally and internationally. And as the jobs and population growth figures attest, more people are listening. — Minneapolis Star Tribune Editorials from newspapers around the state of Minnesota.'}]

Updated: June 2, 2024 @ 12:17 am The economy is showing good signs for consumers. Jobs are readily available to most, inflation is down to a mostly normal 3%, and people are traveling more. But there’s one aspect that is going to cause some consumer pain for the next couple of months — flying. Thanks to the blown-out door plug on the Alaska Airlines flight, all 737 Max 9 (a new variant of the 737 Max 8 that was grounded after two crashes back in 2018) planes in the U.S. have been grounded. That is 171 planes across carriers United and Alaska, the only airlines currently flying the plane in the U.S. We’re still waiting on the FAA investigation to determine the actual cause of the failure and until then flights are going to be a bit more expensive for us. With 171 planes across United and Alaska airlines that cannot fly right now, those routes have to be accommodated with other planes. As you can imagine, airlines don’t just keep spare planes around. So both United and Alaska are going to have to change where they have each of their planes and what routes those planes are on to try to accommodate passengers who would normally be on the grounded planes. All of that means fewer flights for us to take. Many people who would normally fly Alaska or United will now have to fly a different airline. This means rising costs for the rest of us. So let’s talk about what went wrong and why this is Boeing’s fault (again?). Boeing manufactures the 737 with enough doors to accommodate emergency exits for the maximum number of passengers. If an airline wants to cram their passengers in as tightly as possible all of the emergency exit doors are needed. But some airlines, like Alaska, don’t treat their passengers like sardines and give us more room. Because there are fewer passengers on the plane, fewer emergency exits are needed. The exits that aren’t needed are plugged with what’s called a door plug. From the inside of the plane you wouldn’t know the difference, it looks just like the rest of the plane. There’s a good chance many of us have flown right next to a door plug and didn’t know it. The door plug is tested several times throughout manufacturing the plane, including pressurization tests to ensure the plane can remain pressurized while in flight. On this particular plane the pressurization warning light came on during a couple of the previous flights. While that does seem to speak to lax maintenance on the part of Alaska, I’ve read that this warning light is much like the check engine light on our cars. There could be any number of reasons it came on including the sensor being faulty. Instead of playing the blame game, Boeing admitted fault in this case. It’s possible that there was an issue during the manufacture of the plane, or the fix could just be doing extra maintenance on the door plugs to ensure they are secure. We’ll have to wait to find out. It is extremely lucky that no one was killed or injured because of this blow out. Looking at the photos of it, there is a seat right next to the hole in the fuselage, and while I’m sure many items were sucked out of the plane (a few iPhones have been found that were ejected from the flight), no person was. It isn’t always convenient, but it is important to keep your seatbelts fasted while flying. It may save your life. — Jason Ogaard is a software engineer who formerly lived in Hutchinson. Updated: June 2, 2024 @ 12:21 am Now, more than ever, the world needs trustworthy reporting—but good journalism isn’t free. Please support us by subscribing or making a contribution. “Readers Digest” is a 100-year-old publication with a global circulation of more than 10.5 million readers. “Good Morning America” is the number one nationally televised morning news show in the United States. Closer to home, Boyd Huppert’s “Land of 10,000 Stories” on KARE-11 is the recipient of numerous awards in news writing and photojournalism. And Jonathan Werner — celebrated for selling more popcorn than any Boy Scout in Minnesota and spending his earnings on presents for foster children — has been featured in all three. But make no mistake: When the 13-year-old Mora boy set out on his quest to buy Christmas gifts for needy children, publicity was the last thing on his mind. “I didn’t really want the news attention, but I decided to do it because I thought it would have a good impact on scouting and reflect a good image on my council (Troop 506 of Ham Lake) and on scouting as a whole,” the incredibly articulate teenager said. Jonathan’s story goes like this: In 2020, he set a goal to sell $10,000 worth of popcorn, “just to push myself, and because I also wanted a Lego set as a prize for being number one in my council. So I thought, the next year, why not try to be number one?” The next year, he heard his father Steven Kolk talking about the sparse Christmases he experienced as a child in foster care, which prompted Jonathan to become a philanthropist. He sold more than $46,000 worth of popcorn, earning enough in rewards — around $5,000 — to buy presents for foster kids in Kanabec and Isanti Counties. Surprise fame It was 2022 that brought him the most notoriety. Jonathan sold $56,396 worth of popcorn — the most of any Scout in Minnesota and among the top three in the United States. He used $11,300 in rewards to purchase Christmas gifts for needy children in Kanabec, Isanti, Pine, Chisago and northern Anoka Counties. “We had boxes and boxes of presents from floor to ceiling,” his mother Serena Kolk noted. “My son Steven’s room — because he had the most open floor space — that’s where we stored the presents. It was just filled. He had just a path.” Last year was an off year due to a slow economy. He seems almost ashamed when he admits he sold only $51,000 worth of popcorn, but perks up when he notes that he was able to purchase $12,000 in gifts for kids in Kanabec, Isanti, Pine, Chisago Counties, and he added children from the Mille Lacs Band of Ojibwe to his roster. Just buying that many gifts — often more than 600 — is a task unto itself. When he decided to start this project, he first had to figure out how to find the foster kids, so he made a phone call to Kanabec County. Once he made that first call, he was able to be directed to the proper office where he obtained the wish lists of children. Once he knew the appropriate office to reach out to, making calls to other counties came easy to him. He has never met any of the children he has purchased gifts for, which he understands because of privacy issues, although he has received thank yous. “I’ve gotten four or five private notes. A couple of them even drew pictures,” he said. Up next The popcorn-selling season starts the third week of September. Typically, Jonathan sets an overall sales goal for the year, and then breaks it down into weekly sales goals and then daily goals. Since he is home-schooled, he starts his schooling in early August, so he can use most of October to sell popcorn. His mother points out, however, that, unlike public school students, Jonathan and his younger brother, Steven, and sister, Georgina, don’t get the same breaks for holidays, so they manage to get all of their schoolwork completed when other kids have days off. Serena is the Cub Scout leader for Steven and Georgina’s troop in Isanti, where Jonathan serves as a den chief, a type of youth leader who helps with the Cub Scouts. He’s also in National Youth Leadership training as a staff member, so he’s teaching others. He attends monthly staff development and a week-long course at Fred C. Andersen Scout Camp in Wisconsin. He is also a member of the Order of the Arrow, the National Honor Society for scouting, for which he is a constellation chief. Soon, he hopes to join the Civil Air Patrol Cadets. Goals he has in scouting include becoming an Eagle Scout; earning all of the merit badges offered and as many of the extra awards as he possibly can; and finally seeing his fund-raising and gift-buying project go statewide. “I’m going to work with my Boy Scout Council to get a non-profit started to get this project off the ground,” he said. For his Eagle Scout project, he hopes to do something that would benefit veterans, since he has many veterans and military personnel in his life. When his great-grandfather was still alive, Jonathan often visited the veteran’s home in St. Cloud and entertained the residents by playing his violin. Because of his interest in working with veterans, attending ceremonies, dropping off popcorn for their events, and visiting them at the veterans home and bringing them thank you cards, in January, Jonathan was awarded the National American Legion Auxiliary Youth Good Deed Award at a ceremony in Pine City. He was nominated for the award by Linda Setterlund, who saw his donation bucket was focused on soldiers and veterans. “When she heard about what I do, she decided I was worthy of this award,” he said. Long-term During COVID, Jonathan had to stop his veterans home visits, but he hopes to begin again, if he can find the time. As a scout, he also does flag placement and wreath clean-up at cemeteries. On Saturday, Feb. 3, he was at Fort Snelling, helping with gathering the hundreds of Christmas wreaths for disposal. So enamored of the military is he that he hopes to attend either the United States Air Force Academy or the United States Naval Academy when he graduates from high school, with his eye on being part of the Judge Advocate Corps. But that’s all in the future. After all, he’s only 13, something that’s easy to forget in conversation with him. Right now, his aim is to stick with the popcorn-selling project for next year and keep buying gifts for foster kids. “That not only helps me and the foster kids, it helps my troop, my council, and the Boy Scouts at the national level to operate their different programs,” he said. And if that means he has to get a little more publicity? The event included the unveiling of the auditoriums new seating. NEW ULM — Where is the best seat in town? After two months of renovations, it’s at State Street Theater. The historic theater began replacing its old wooden seating with new modern seats. As of this week, the auditorium has a total of 703 new, comfortable chairs as well as additional ADA-compliant seating. A special unveiling ceremony was held for the renovated auditorium, which included a brief program on the history of the theater. Historian Dr. Dan Groebner, who has researched the theater for years described the renovations as “breathtaking.” Groebner explained the theater was originally built in 1939 as a Works Progress Administration (WPA) project. The theater was originally part of New Ulm High School, serving as auditorium/gym space. The building eventually transitioned into Middle School. It was for this reason the theater was originally built with narrow wooden seating. By 2012, the school district was no longer using the building as a school and was looking to sell it. Eventually, it was sold to a local citizen group called Cenate LLC. Cenate’s purpose was to find a solution to housing shortages and turn ownership of the gym/auditorium over to a performing arts group. The renovation of State Street Theaters auditorium was completed this week. Among the renovations was the replacement of the old narrow wooden seats with wider cushioned seats. After the sale of the classroom side of the building, Cenate gave the theater space over to New Ulm Actors Community Theatre, which officially changed its name to State Street Theater Company (SSTC). Over the years, State Street Theater has raised over $1 million through capital campaigns. The early campaigns were designed to update infrastructure, with the most recent campaign to improve the aesthetics of the space. SSTC President Emeritus Mary Ellen Domeier said it was the current campaign that covered the cost of replacing the seating. The aim was to keep the auditorium in the style of a 1939 theater, but have more modern seating. The old wooden seats are the most frequent complaint from audiences. Domeier explained the old wooden seats were only 17 inches wide. The new seats are between 20 and 22 inches wide. In addition, to the seats safety railings were added to the steep balcony. Aisle lights were added to all parts of the theater. Several donors and volunteers were thanked for making the renovations possible. Mikelson Medica Foundation and the Roger & Carol Ryberg Family Trust each donated over $100,000 to the project. Seating improvements at State Street included safety upgrades to the balcony. New railings were installed along the stairs. “It is not often we can have an effect on the quality of life in a community and we have here,” Roger Ryberg said. He believed the arts were needed to give a community a high-quality life and these renovations were a part of making that possible. “I look forward to enjoying these 22-inch seats,” Ryberg said. Thor Mickelson said it was amazing to be part of a community that cares so much to make the theater renovations possible. He credited strong leadership and many volunteers for making this project possible. SSTC’s board of directors also wished to thank four of the earliest volunteers for getting the theater company started and continuing to thrive. Judy Sellner, Brenda Nielsen, Wendy Tuttle and Tom Kaehler were given special certificates of appreciation for their volunteer work with SSTC. State Street Theater volunteers (L to R): Judy Sellner, Wendy Tuttle and Tom Kaehler received certificates of appreciate for the countless hours of support they have rendered to the theater. The program closed with a special proclamation, read by New Ulm City Council President Andrea Boettger, declaring Feb. 9, 2024, State Street Theater Day. The first show to be held at SSTC with the new seating is “Chase & Ovation A Salute to the Music of Prince. The performance will be held at 7 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 10. the text is written entirely by a human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': "We are excited to announce that we are going to the Chanhassen Dinner Theater to see the musical “Beautiful: The Carole King Story.” The soundtrack of a generation inspired this Broadway smash hit! For nearly six years, “Beautiful: The Carole King Musical” thrilled Broadway audiences with the inspiring true story of Carole King’s remarkable journey from teenage songwriter to Rock & Roll Hall of Fame music legend. As a woman in the music industry, King broke barriers and became one of the most prolific songwriters of our time! King and her writing partner, Gerry Goffin, wrote over 20 songs that became chart hits. Many different artists recorded her songs in the 1960s. In 1971 she wrote and recorded the Grammy-winning masterpiece album, “Tapestry.” It was at the top of the U.S. album chart for 15 weeks. It is one of the best-selling albums of all time. King made 25 solo albums. Her most recent album is “Live at the Troubadour”, which she made with James Taylor. This album was No. 4 on the charts in its first week and has sold over 400,000 copies. She has won four Grammy Awards and was inducted into the Songwriters Hall of Fame and the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame for her songwriting. In 2009, Carole King was admitted into the Hit Parade Hall of Fame. Carole wrote hits for the biggest music acts from The Shirelles to The Righteous Brothers. The musical takes you on a joy-filled, emotional ride of a lifetime! Featuring over two dozen hits including “One Fine Day,” “The Locomotion,” “So Far Away,” “Natural Woman,” “You’ve Lost That Lovin’ Feelin,’” and “Will You Love Me Tomorrow,” this Tony and Grammy Award-winning musical is filled with the songs you remember and a story you’ll never forget. A huge cast of singers and dancers bring more than 24 of her greatest hits to life in a triumphant celebration! Call the Senior Center, 507-263-2136, to make your reservation for the matinee show on Saturday, March 15. The cost is $125 for CVSC members and $135 for non-members. The price includes transportation, dinner and gratuity. Join us and leave the driving to us! If you haven’t signed up for a CVSC membership, now would be a good time to save $10 on your trip for a $20 membership for the year. Plus, you’ll receive discounts from local businesses and other benefits at CVSC programs and events. We’re hosting an open house! Join us Tuesday, Feb. 13, from 1-3 p.m. at the CVSC. We’ll be serving treats and refreshments. Come in and learn more about our programs and events. John Lyons from Landmark Tours will speak at 2 p.m. about traveling with their company, which also benefits the CVSC when you travel with them. This event is free and open to the public. Feeling a little crafty? We’ll be making 3-D paper heart decorations and painting rocks that we’ll place around town on Monday, Feb. 12, at 11 a.m. These are easy and fun to create! Members are free of charge, non-members $5. Join us for “It’s Coffee Time!” at 10 a.m. and fire up for some crafting fun afterwards! Who to help? How to help? These questions will be covered by Shannon Bauer, the “Needs Assessor” of the Good Samaritan Fund helping people in need in the Cannon Falls area at the Wednesday, Feb. 14 meeting of the Cannon Falls Area Triad - Citizens and Law Enforcement Partnership at 10 a.m. at the Cannon Valley Senior Center, 120 State Street West, Cannon Falls. Bauer explained that his master’s degree in Family Systems Theory has been helpful in this project. “In vetting those seeking Good Samaritan funds - spirit-led discernment is very important. In getting to know those in need,sometimes it is about recognizing unhealthy patterns over blindly giving funds. Helping people with the resources to seek a healthy lifestyle is a joy in this ministry,” said Bauer. “Also taking the time to listen and discern helps to weed out the scammers. Unfortunately, close to half of the Good Samaritan requests come from a scam. I look forward to sharing a few of these stories of help and God’s wisdom with you on Feb. 14.” Other topics of interest at the meeting include dialogue with local Cannon Falls Police Officers and Goodhue County Deputies. Hope to see you there! It seems there are lots of smiles when it comes to this record-breaking mild weather we’re experiencing lately. As someone that does enjoy the snow and the beauty of winter, I’m really enjoying the ease of living in this! Although, I have also had concerns over what these warm temps are doing to our plants. Looking into this, I found some relief from learning from the Minnesota Arboretum, that plants don’t respond to temperature only, but through daylight hours of sun. Some buds you might see might have developed in the fall and is not unusual. Mulching a little extra around perennials will help with temperature differences if the cold does come around to get us. Also, keeping track of trees and plants that get through these extremes are good to note if you plan on new plantings on your property. I’ve been surprised to see my parsley and thyme getting green! Unfortunately, this warm winter could mean ecological ripple effects on Minnesota forests, and wildlife according to the Minnesota DNR. Climate change is happening and is a study on its own. We’re also experiencing a strong El Nino, a warming of the ocean surface, or above-average sea surface temperatures, in the central and eastern tropical Pacific Ocean, that is affecting our weather. I’ve heard from maple syrup-making enthusiasts that they’re worried about sap running early and some have reported that the Goldfinches are starting to turn to their summer plumage. My hope is that we adapt as best that we can to our changing environment. In the meantime, enjoy this great weather! Put away your cross country skis and get your bicycle out. The Cannon Valley Trail has been cleared of winter debris and ready for you to roll! Do be aware of possible black ice. If you’re in need of some even earlier spring experiences, go to the Spring Flower Show at the Minnesota Landscape Arboretum from Thursday, Feb. 8, 6 p.m. until Sunday, March 10, 6 p.m. The Cannon Valley Senior Center is raising funds for our third annual $1,000 scholarship to a Cannon Falls High School graduate. On March 16, from 9 a.m. until 2 p.m., we will be hosting a Spring Hometown Boutique and Market as a scholarship fundraiser. If you are a vendor that would like to participate in this event, please call the CVSC at 507-263-2136, or email at lora@cannonvalleyseniorcenter.org. The Cannon Valley Senior Center is open Monday – Thursday, 9 a.m. until 1 p.m. Look for us on Facebook and like us! human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': '-Advertisement- Several years ago, I interviewed Julie at Dignity House. She was connecting twice a week with an advocate there to build stability back into her life after an accident that left her with brain damage, which led to the loss of her job, which ultimately led to being unhoused. Publisher Mikki Morrissette It has been seven years since I talked to her, but something I remember to this day is that she told me one of the items on her wish list was to be able to afford to wear new undergarments again, instead of hand-me-downs. As someone who has generally been steadily housed and employed, this detail about dignity is something I had never considered. It struck me how much I did not know about what Julie, and others impacted by the kinds of challenges she faced, had to navigate. Julie told me that the advocate she worked with helped her feel someone cared and wanted to see her succeed. She rediscovered that she mattered. “I lost that for a while,” she said. “Not knowing where to turn is humiliating. I became simply another number. One of those people who needs help instead of a person.” Two years ago, I met April Chouinard, who appreciated having a place in Saint Peter to recover from substance use. She told me she was supported by her peers at Solace after she relapsed. “To be able to stay gave me a huge sense that I am worth something — that even if I cannot love myself yet, they do,” Chouinard said. “All of a sudden you feel like somebody has your back and you matter. You are not just an addict. That grace is huge.” More recently, I visited Peace House, where unhoused people arrive for an afternoon lunch, conversation about a question of the day, and sometimes a massage, haircut, or bike repair. The house was opened in 1985 by Sister Rose Tillemans with a mission to provide a welcoming space for people who tend to otherwise not be invited over for dinner. She wanted to offer an opportunity to share conversation for “those who had no one to listen to them.” Thanks to 2023 bipartisan legislative work, Minnesota currently has historic financial and policy support to help solve long-simmering underinvestment in housing. The people featured in this issue recognize that dignity, support, respect, and a sense of belonging are invaluable to the foundation that comes from housing. We unpack statewide needs, share data, and begin to explore with advocates, government voices, and community- based innovators some of the solutions in process, even as experts — who include people with experiences of housing instability — sort out what the right next steps might be and how best to get there. Winner of six awards in 2023, including Community Service and Best Magazine article related to our gender-based violence coverage, social media campaign for Badass membership, and three awards for photographer Sarah Whiting. Minnesota Women’s Press has been sharing the authentic voice and powerful vision of women since 1985, as one of the longest running feminist platforms (print and digital) in the U.S. Please donate to support our story sharing and free distribution to more than 500 sites. Telephone: 651-646-3968 Mailing Address: 800 West Broadway #3A Minneapolis, MN 55411'}]

Updated: June 2, 2024 @ 12:10 am 20 YEARS AGO: NEWS FROM THE ISSUE OF FEB. 12, 2004 Litchfield School District hit a snag with the Minnesota Department of Education in regard to its $20 million bond proposal to update school facilities. Superintendent Bill Wold told the School Board Monday that the Department of Education is ready to approve the $18.5 million portion of the project involving the high school and middle school. However, the department is hesitant to approve $1.5 million for the renovation of Bernie Aaker Auditorium because the district does not own the property. The Family Services Building, which houses the auditorium, is owned by Meeker County and the school district has 32 years left on a long-term lease with the county. It may have created some rocky times during the past several months, but the transition of Litchfield Public Utilities from a kind of autonomous business to a department of the city of Litchfield seems on track now. Administrator Bruce Miller said the transition is accomplishing a “streamlined package here (with) a whole list of goals to accomplish in 2024.” Among the goals was creation of an automatic meter reading system for city electric and water systems, and installation of a seamless billing program between the utilities and city administration. “It’s fun to have a rivalry like that,” first-year Litchfield/Dassel-Cokato boys hockey coach Chris Olson said after LDC and Willmar skated to a 2-2 tie last month. “Best hockey game I ever saw,” was the reaction of Independent Review sports editor Lyle Diekmann. “The game proved that the Cardinal-Dragon rivalry is still alive and skating,” wrote Rand Middleton of the West Central Tribune. “It’s one high school game that gets everyone’s blood pumping a little faster …” Yet after meeting twice yearly since 1972 when Willmar started playing hockey (two years, incidentally, after Litchfield started its program), the Litch-Willmar hockey rivalry — one of the keenest in any sport anywhere in the state — will be cut back to a single game next year with the Willmar school administration making the call. — Stan Roeser, Lookin’ Around Litch Litchfield’s Dan Foley bowled his first 300 game and became the fist person to roll an 800 series at Litchfield Bowling Center during Tuesday Early League Action Jan. 27. Foley posted games of 266, 300 and 244 for an 810 series. Foley finished his night with 31 strikes, four spares and one open frame, not to shabby for a bowler who sported a 127 average as a beginner 12 years ago. “The ball was to be in the right spot but the pins have to fall,” Foley said of his big night. “I got lucky.” 95 YEARS AGO: NEWS FROM THE ISSUE OF FEB. 16, 1929 Litchfield lost its earliest community builder Thursday evening in the death of Erhardt Lenhardt at the age of almost 85 years. Mr. Lenhardt became ill about a month ago and three weeks ago was moved from his home to the Lenhardt Hotel, where he was in the charge of a trained nurse. He was born in 1844 in Saxony, Germany. With his wife and little daughter, who later became Mrs. William Lenhard, he immigrated from Germany in 1873, arriving in Litchfield on July 4 that year. Mr. Lenhardt became a man of prominence in Litchfield through diligence, thrift and high degree of community spirit. During his years here there was not one movement for the betterment of our community which did not get his support. Litchfield’s splendid sewage system is due to his urging and support. More than 25 years years ago he became owner of the Litchfield hotel, which he improved from time to time and with the adding of a coffee shop only last year the facility became one of the best of its kind in the entire state.
